---
description: API development standards for FastAPI endpoints and OpenAI-compatible interfaces
alwaysApply: false
globs: oricli_core/api/**/*.py
---

# Cursor Rules: API Development Standards

rules:
  - id: api.structure.fastapi_patterns
    description: |
      All API endpoints must follow FastAPI best practices and established patterns.
      - Use FastAPI dependency injection for shared logic (auth, validation, etc.)
      - Use Pydantic models for request/response validation
      - Use type hints for all function parameters and return types
      - Group related endpoints using FastAPI routers when appropriate
      - Use descriptive endpoint function names that indicate their purpose
      - Document endpoints with docstrings and OpenAPI tags
    severity: error

  - id: api.structure.endpoint_naming
    description: |
      API endpoints must follow RESTful naming conventions.
      - Use HTTP verbs appropriately (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH)
      - Use plural nouns for resource collections (e.g., `/v1/modules`, `/v1/metrics`)
      - Use singular nouns or IDs for individual resources (e.g., `/v1/modules/{module_name}`)
      - Use kebab-case for URL paths
      - Version all endpoints with `/v1/` prefix
      - Use descriptive path segments that indicate resource hierarchy
    severity: error

  - id: api.structure.openai_compatibility
    description: |
      OpenAI-compatible endpoints must strictly adhere to OpenAI API specifications.
      - `/v1/chat/completions` must match OpenAI Chat Completions API format
      - `/v1/embeddings` must match OpenAI Embeddings API format
      - `/v1/models` must return models list in OpenAI format
      - Request/response schemas must be compatible with OpenAI clients
      - Error responses must follow OpenAI error format
      - Streaming responses must use Server-Sent Events (SSE) format
    severity: error

  - id: api.validation.request_validation
    description: |
      All API requests must be validated using Pydantic models.
      - Define Pydantic models for all request bodies
      - Use field validators for complex validation logic
      - Validate required fields, types, and constraints
      - Provide clear validation error messages
      - Use FastAPI's automatic validation and error responses
      - Document validation rules in model docstrings
    severity: error

  - id: api.validation.response_formatting
    description: |
      API responses must follow consistent formatting standards.
      - Use Pydantic models for all response bodies
      - Include standard response fields (status, data, errors when applicable)
      - Use consistent error response format across all endpoints
      - Include request metadata (request_id, timestamp) when appropriate
      - Document response schemas in OpenAPI documentation
    severity: error

  - id: api.error_handling.error_responses
    description: |
      Error responses must be consistent and informative.
      - Use appropriate HTTP status codes (400, 401, 403, 404, 500, etc.)
      - Return structured error responses with error codes and messages
      - Include context in error responses (field names, validation details)
      - Use FastAPI's HTTPException for standard HTTP errors
      - Log errors with appropriate context before returning responses
      - Never expose internal implementation details in error messages
    severity: error

  - id: api.error_handling.exception_mapping
    description: |
      Internal exceptions must be mapped to appropriate HTTP responses.
      - Map MavaiaError exceptions to appropriate HTTP status codes
      - Map ModuleError to 500 with module context
      - Map AuthenticationError to 401
      - Map ValidationError to 400
      - Map ModuleNotFoundError to 404
      - Use exception handlers to centralize exception-to-response mapping
    severity: error

  - id: api.authentication.patterns
    description: |
      Authentication must be implemented consistently across all protected endpoints.
      - Use API key authentication via `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header
      - Validate API keys using dependency injection
      - Support optional authentication (validate if provided, allow if not required)
      - Support required authentication mode (reject requests without valid key)
      - Store API keys securely (environment variables, secrets management)
      - Never log or expose API keys in error messages or logs
    severity: error

  - id: api.authentication.dependency_injection
    description: |
      Use FastAPI dependency injection for authentication logic.
      - Create authentication dependency functions
      - Reuse authentication dependencies across endpoints
      - Support both optional and required authentication modes
      - Return user/request context from authentication dependencies
      - Document authentication requirements in endpoint docstrings
    severity: error

  - id: api.documentation.openapi
    description: |
      All endpoints must be properly documented in OpenAPI/Swagger.
      - Use descriptive endpoint summaries and descriptions
      - Tag endpoints appropriately for organization
      - Document all request parameters, bodies, and responses
      - Include example requests and responses
      - Document error responses and status codes
      - Keep OpenAPI documentation up-to-date with code changes
    severity: error

  - id: api.documentation.endpoint_docstrings
    description: |
      All endpoint functions must have comprehensive docstrings.
      - Document endpoint purpose and behavior
      - Document request parameters and their types
      - Document response format and status codes
      - Document authentication requirements
      - Document error conditions and their responses
      - Include usage examples when helpful
    severity: warning

  - id: api.versioning.strategy
    description: |
      API versioning must follow semantic versioning principles.
      - All endpoints must be versioned with `/v1/` prefix
      - Breaking changes require new version (e.g., `/v2/`)
      - Non-breaking changes can be made within the same version
      - Document version changes in API changelog
      - Support multiple API versions simultaneously during transition periods
      - Deprecate old versions with clear migration paths
    severity: error

  - id: api.middleware.cors
    description: |
      CORS middleware must be configured appropriately.
      - Enable CORS for development and production environments
      - Configure allowed origins based on environment
      - Use specific origins in production, not wildcards
      - Configure allowed methods and headers appropriately
      - Document CORS configuration in deployment guides
    severity: warning

  - id: api.middleware.logging
    description: |
      API requests and responses must be logged appropriately.
      - Log all incoming requests with metadata (method, path, client IP)
      - Log request processing time
      - Log errors with full context
      - Do not log sensitive data (API keys, passwords, PII)
      - Use structured logging for better observability
      - Include request IDs for traceability
    severity: warning

  - id: api.tools.registration
    description: |
      Tool registration must follow established patterns.
      - Register tools using ToolRegistry
      - Define tool schemas with proper parameter validation
      - Document tool handlers with clear docstrings
      - Handle tool execution errors gracefully
      - Return tool results in consistent format
      - Support tool versioning and deprecation
    severity: error

  - id: api.tools.handler_patterns
    description: |
      Tool handlers must follow consistent patterns.
      - Tool handlers must accept typed parameters
      - Validate tool parameters before execution
      - Execute tool operations using module registry
      - Return results in standardized tool result format
      - Handle errors and return appropriate error responses
      - Document tool behavior and limitations
    severity: error

  - id: api.performance.response_time
    description: |
      API endpoints must meet performance requirements.
      - Health check endpoints must respond in <100ms
      - Simple read operations must respond in <500ms
      - Complex operations must respond in <5s or support async/streaming
      - Use async endpoints for long-running operations
      - Implement request timeouts appropriately
      - Monitor and alert on slow endpoints
    severity: warning

  - id: api.quality.type_safety
    description: |
      All API code must use type hints and type checking.
      - Use type hints for all function parameters and return types
      - Use Pydantic models for request/response validation
      - Run mypy type checking in CI/CD
      - Fix type errors before merging code
      - Use `typing` module for complex types (Optional, List, Dict, etc.)
    severity: error

examples:
  - description: "Standard FastAPI endpoint with authentication"
    language: python
    code: |
      from fastapi import APIRouter, Depends, HTTPException, Header
      from typing import Optional
      from oricli_core.types.models import ChatCompletionRequest, ChatCompletionResponse
      from oricli_core.exceptions import AuthenticationError
      
      
      router = APIRouter(prefix="/v1", tags=["chat"])
      
      
      async def verify_api_key(
          authorization: Optional[str] = Header(None),
          api_key: Optional[str] = None,
          require_auth: bool = False
      ) -> Optional[str]:
          """
          Verify API key from Authorization header
          
          Args:
              authorization: Authorization header value
              api_key: Expected API key
              require_auth: Whether authentication is required
          
          Returns:
              API key if valid, None if optional and not provided
          
          Raises:
              HTTPException: If authentication fails
          """
          if not api_key:
              if require_auth:
                  raise HTTPException(status_code=401, detail="API key required")
              return None
          
          if not authorization or not authorization.startswith("Bearer "):
              if require_auth:
                  raise HTTPException(status_code=401, detail="Invalid authorization header")
              return None
          
          token = authorization.replace("Bearer ", "")
          if token != api_key:
              raise HTTPException(status_code=401, detail="Invalid API key")
          
          return token
      
      
      @router.post("/chat/completions", response_model=ChatCompletionResponse)
      async def create_chat_completion(
          request: ChatCompletionRequest,
          api_key: Optional[str] = Depends(verify_api_key)
      ) -> ChatCompletionResponse:
          """
          Create a chat completion
          
          Args:
              request: Chat completion request
              api_key: Verified API key (from dependency)
          
          Returns:
              Chat completion response
          
          Raises:
              HTTPException: For validation or processing errors
          """
          # Implementation here
          pass

  - description: "Error handling with exception mapping"
    language: python
    code: |
      from fastapi import FastAPI, HTTPException, Request
      from fastapi.responses import JSONResponse
      from oricli_core.exceptions import (
          MavaiaError,
          AuthenticationError,
          ValidationError,
          ModuleNotFoundError
      )
      
      
      app = FastAPI()
      
      
      @app.exception_handler(AuthenticationError)
      async def authentication_error_handler(request: Request, exc: AuthenticationError):
          """Handle authentication errors"""
          return JSONResponse(
              status_code=401,
              content={
                  "error": {
                      "message": str(exc),
                      "type": "authentication_error",
                      "code": "invalid_api_key"
                  }
              }
          )
      
      
      @app.exception_handler(ValidationError)
      async def validation_error_handler(request: Request, exc: ValidationError):
          """Handle validation errors"""
          return JSONResponse(
              status_code=400,
              content={
                  "error": {
                      "message": str(exc),
                      "type": "validation_error",
                      "field": exc.field,
                      "code": "invalid_parameter"
                  }
              }
          )
      
      
      @app.exception_handler(ModuleNotFoundError)
      async def module_not_found_handler(request: Request, exc: ModuleNotFoundError):
          """Handle module not found errors"""
          return JSONResponse(
              status_code=404,
              content={
                  "error": {
                      "message": str(exc),
                      "type": "module_not_found",
                      "code": "module_not_found"
                  }
              }
          )

